<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDream_interpretation&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Early_civilizations">Early =
civilizations</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DDream_interpretation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Early civilizations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Tablet_V_of_the_Epic_of_Gilgamesh.jpg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/1/13/Tablet_V_of_the_Epic_of_Gilgamesh.jpg/250px-Tablet_V_of=
_the_Epic_of_Gilgamesh.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"323"=
 class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2705" data-file-height=3D"349=
7"></a><figcaption>The ancient <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akk=
adian_language" title=3D"Akkadian language">Akkadian</a> <i><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epic_of_Gilgamesh" title=3D"Epic of Gilgamesh">Ep=
ic of Gilgamesh</a></i> (<i>Tablet V pictured</i>) contains numerous exampl=
es of dream interpretation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-BlackGreen1992_4-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#c=
ite_note-BlackGreen1992-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></figcaption></figure>
<p>The ancient <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sumer" title=3D"Sum=
er">Sumerians</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mesopotamia" =
title=3D"Mesopotamia">Mesopotamia</a> have left evidence of dream interpret=
ation dating back to at least 3100 BC.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Seligman_5-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretat=
ion#cite_note-Seligman-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-BlackGreen1992_4-1"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpr=
etation#cite_note-BlackGreen1992-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Throughout Mesopotamian hist=
ory, dreams were always held to be extremely important for <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divination" title=3D"Divination">divination</a><su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-BlackGreen1992_4-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-BlackGreen1992-4"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Oppenheim_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-Oppenheim-6"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> and Mesopotamian kings paid close attention to them.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-BlackGreen1992_4-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-BlackGreen1992-4"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-Seligman_5-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-Seligman-5"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gudea" title=3D"Gudea">Gudea</a>, the ki=
ng of the Sumerian city-state of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L=
agash" title=3D"Lagash">Lagash</a> (reigned <abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr>=
 2144=E2=80=932124 BC), rebuilt the temple of <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Ningirsu" title=3D"Ningirsu">Ningirsu</a> as a result of a drea=
m in which he was told to do so.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-BlackGreen1992_4-4" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretat=
ion#cite_note-BlackGreen1992-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Gudea dreamed of a huge and powe=
rful figure who looked part god, part bird, and part storm, with lions besi=
de him to show his strength. This figure told Gudea to build a temple, but =
Gudea did not fully understand the message. Ningirsu also promised to send =
gentle rain and good weather so the building would be successful, which sho=
ws that people at the time believed dreams were important messages that cam=
e during sleep when the mind was quiet and open.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretati=
on#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The standard <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akkadian_langu=
age" title=3D"Akkadian language">Akkadian</a> <i><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Epic_of_Gilgamesh" title=3D"Epic of Gilgamesh">Epic of Gilga=
mesh</a></i> contains numerous accounts of the prophetic power of dreams.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-BlackGreen1992_4-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-BlackGreen1992-4"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream=
_interpretation#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> First, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Gilgamesh" title=3D"Gilgamesh">Gilgamesh</a> himself has two d=
reams foretelling the arrival of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
nkidu" title=3D"Enkidu">Enkidu</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-BlackGreen1992_4-6" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpre=
tation#cite_note-BlackGreen1992-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In one of these dreams, Gilga=
mesh sees an axe fall from the sky. The people gather around it in admirati=
on and worship. Gilgamesh throws the axe in front of his mother <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ninsun" title=3D"Ninsun">Ninsun</a> and then =
embraces it like a wife. Ninsun interprets the dream to mean that someone p=
owerful will soon appear. Gilgamesh will struggle with him and try to overp=
ower him, but he will not succeed. Eventually, they will become close frien=
ds and accomplish great things. She concludes, "That you embraced him like =
a wife means he will never forsake you. Thus your dream is solved."<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Later in the epic, Enkidu=
 dreams about the heroes' encounter with the giant <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Humbaba" title=3D"Humbaba">Humbaba</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-BlackGreen1992_4-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-BlackGreen1992-4"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Dreams w=
ere also sometimes seen as a means of seeing into other worlds<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-BlackGreen1992_4-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-BlackGreen1992-4"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
and it was thought that the soul, or some part of it, moved out of the body=
 of the sleeping person and actually visited the places and persons the dre=
amer saw in his or her sleep.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2_11-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-=
:2-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> In Tablet VII of the epic, Enkidu recounts to Gilgamesh =
a dream in which he saw the gods <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A=
nu" title=3D"Anu">Anu</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enlil" =
title=3D"Enlil">Enlil</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sha=
mash" title=3D"Shamash">Shamash</a> condemn him to death.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-BlackGreen1992_4-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-BlackGreen1992-4"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> He also=
 has a dream in which he visits the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Kur" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Kur">Underworld</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-BlackGreen1992_4-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-BlackGreen1992-4"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Assyria" title=3D"Assyr=
ia">Assyrian</a> king <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ashurnasirpa=
l_II" title=3D"Ashurnasirpal II">Ashurnasirpal II</a> (reigned 883=E2=80=93=
859 BC) built a temple to Mamu, possibly the god of dreams, at <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imgur-Enlil" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Im=
gur-Enlil">Imgur-Enlil</a>, near <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K=
alhu" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Kalhu">Kalhu</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-B=
lackGreen1992_4-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-BlackGreen1992-4"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The later=
 Assyrian king <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ashurbanipal" title=
=3D"Ashurbanipal">Ashurbanipal</a> (reigned 668=E2=80=93<abbr title=3D"circ=
a">c.</abbr> 627 BC) had a dream during a desperate military situation in w=
hich his divine patron, the goddess <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Inanna" title=3D"Inanna">Ishtar</a>, appeared to him and promised that sh=
e would lead him to victory.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-BlackGreen1992_4-12" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretatio=
n#cite_note-BlackGreen1992-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Babylonia" title=3D"Babylonia">Babylonians</a> and Assyrians div=
ided dreams into "good," which were sent by the gods, and "bad," sent by de=
mons.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Oppenheim_6-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-Oppenheim-6"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> A surviving collection of dream omens entitled <i><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I%C5%A1kar_Zaq%C4%ABqu" title=3D"I=C5=A1kar Zaq=C4=AB=
qu">I=C5=A1kar Zaq=C4=ABqu</a></i> records various dream scenarios as well =
as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prognosis" title=3D"Prognosis">=
prognostications</a> of what will happen to the person who experiences each=
 dream, apparently based on previous cases.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-BlackGreen19=
92_4-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream=
_interpretation#cite_note-BlackGreen1992-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-1=
2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_inter=
pretation#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Some list different possible outcomes,=
 based on occasions in which people experienced similar dreams with differe=
nt results.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-BlackGreen1992_4-14" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-BlackG=
reen1992-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> Dream scenarios mentioned include a variety of daily=
 work events, journeys to different locations, family matters, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_sexual_activity" title=3D"Human sexual a=
ctivity">sex acts</a>, and encounters with human individuals, animals, and =
deities.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-BlackGreen1992_4-15" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-BlackGree=
n1992-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Tissot_Joseph_Interprets_Pharaoh%27s_Dream.jpg=
" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wi=
kipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/Tissot_Joseph_Interprets_Pharaoh%27s_Dream.jpg/3=
30px-Tissot_Joseph_Interprets_Pharaoh%27s_Dream.jpg" decoding=3D"async" wid=
th=3D"300" height=3D"200" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"3000=
" data-file-height=3D"2002"></a><figcaption>Joseph Interprets Pharaoh's Dre=
am (watercolor circa 1896=E2=80=931902 by James Tissot)</figcaption></figur=
e>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Egypt" title=3D"Anci=
ent Egypt">ancient Egypt</a>, priests acted as dream interpreters. <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hieroglyph" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Hieroglyph">Hieroglyphics</a> depicting dreams and their interpretation=
s are evident. Dreams have been held in considerable importance throughout =
history by most cultures.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Classical_Antiquity">Classi=
cal Antiquity</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DDream_interpretation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Classical Antiquity"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Greeks" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Ancient Greeks">ancient Greeks</a> constructed temples =
they called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asclepieion" title=3D"=
Asclepieion">Asclepieions</a>, where sick people were sent to be cured. It =
was believed that cures would be effected through <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Divine_grace" title=3D"Divine grace">divine grace</a> by <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Incubation_(ritual)" title=3D"Incuba=
tion (ritual)">incubating dreams</a> within the confines of the temple. Dre=
ams were also considered prophetic or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Omen" title=3D"Omen">omens</a> of particular significance. <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artemidorus_of_Daldis" title=3D"Artemidorus of=
 Daldis">Artemidorus</a> of Daldis, who lived in the 2nd century AD, wrote =
a comprehensive text <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oneirocrit=
ica" title=3D"Oneirocritica">Oneirocritica</a></i> (<i>The Interpretation o=
f Dreams</i>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Alth=
ough Artemidorus believed that dreams can predict the future, he presaged m=
any contemporary approaches to dreams. He thought that the meaning of a dre=
am image could involve puns and could be understood by decoding the image i=
nto its component words. For example, Alexander, while waging war against t=
he Tyrians, dreamt that a satyr was dancing on his shield. Artemidorus repo=
rts that this dream was interpreted as follows: satyr =3D <i>sa tyros</i> (=
"Tyre will be thine"), predicting that Alexander would be triumphant. Freud=
 acknowledged this example of Artemidorus when he proposed that dreams be i=
nterpreted like a rebus.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Freud,_S._1900_14-0" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cit=
e_note-Freud,_S._1900-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Middle_Ages">Middle Ages</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDream_interpre=
tation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Middle Age=
s"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychology_in_medieval_Islam=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Psychology in medieval Islam">medieval Isl=
amic psychology</a>, certain <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hadit=
h" title=3D"Hadith">hadiths</a> indicate that <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Dream" title=3D"Dream">dreams</a> consist of three parts, and e=
arly <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ulema" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Ulema">Muslim scholars</a> recognized three kinds of dreams: false=
, pathogenic, and true.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Amber-376_15-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note=
-Amber-376-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ibn_Sir=
in" title=3D"Ibn Sirin">Ibn Sirin</a> (654=E2=80=93728) was renowned for hi=
s <i>Ta'bir al-Ru'ya</i> and <i>Muntakhab al-Kalam fi Tabir al-Ahlam</i>, a=
 book on dreams. The work is divided into 25 sections on dream interpretati=
on, from the etiquette of interpreting dreams to the interpretation of reci=
ting certain <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sura" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Sura">Surahs</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Qur%27an" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Qur'an">Qur'an</a> in one's =
dream. He writes that it is important for a layperson to seek assistance fr=
om an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%27alim" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"'alim">alim</a> (Muslim scholar) who could guide in the interpr=
etation of dreams with a proper understanding of the cultural context and o=
ther such causes and interpretations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Amber-375_16-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpreta=
tion#cite_note-Amber-375-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Al-Kindi" title=3D"Al-Kindi">Al-Kindi</a> (Alkindus) (801=E2=80=9387=
3) also wrote a treatise on dream interpretation: <i>On Sleep and Dreams</i=
>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Amber-361_17-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-Amber-361-17"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consciousness" title=3D"C=
onsciousness">consciousness</a> studies, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Al-Farabi" title=3D"Al-Farabi">Al-Farabi</a> (872=E2=80=93951) wrote=
 the <i>On the Cause of Dreams</i>, which appeared as chapter 24 of his <i>=
Book of Opinions of the people of the Ideal City</i>. It was a treatise on =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream" title=3D"Dream">dreams</a>,=
 in which he was the first to distinguish between dream interpretation and =
the nature and causes of dreams.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Amber-363_18-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretatio=
n#cite_note-Amber-363-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/The_Canon_of_Medicine" title=3D"The Canon of Medicine">The Canon =
of Medicine</a></i>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avicenna" tit=
le=3D"Avicenna">Avicenna</a> extended the theory of <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Temperament" title=3D"Temperament">temperaments</a> to en=
compass "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emotion" title=3D"Emotion=
">emotional</a> aspects, mental capacity, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Moral" title=3D"Moral">moral</a> attitudes, <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Self-awareness" title=3D"Self-awareness">self-awareness</=
a>, movements and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream" title=3D"=
Dream">dreams</a>."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Lutz_19-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-Lutz-19"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ibn_Khaldun" title=3D=
"Ibn Khaldun">Ibn Khaldun</a>'s <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Muqaddimah" title=3D"Muqaddimah">Muqaddimah</a></i> (1377) states that "co=
nfused dreams" are "pictures of the imagination that are stored inside by <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perception" title=3D"Perception">pe=
rception</a> and to which the ability to think is applied, after (man) has =
retired from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sense" title=3D"Sense=
">sense</a> perception."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-20"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p><p>Ibn Shaheen states: "Interpretations change their foundations accord=
ing to the different conditions of the seer (of the vision), so seeing hand=
cuffs during sleep is disliked but if a righteous person sees them it can m=
ean stopping the hands from evil". Ibn Sirin said about a man who saw himse=
lf giving a sermon from the mimbar: "He will achieve authority and if he is=
 not from the people who have any kind of authority it means that he will b=
e crucified".
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"China">China</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDream_interpretation&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: China"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A standard traditional Chinese book on dream-interpretation is the <i>Lo=
fty Principles of Dream Interpretation</i> (=E5=A4=A2=E5=8D=A0=E9=80=B8=E6=
=97=A8) compiled in the 16th century by Chen Shiyuan (particularly the "Inn=
er Chapters" of that opus).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-21"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D=
ream_interpretation#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretatio=
n#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> Chinese thinkers also raised profound ideas abo=
ut dream interpretation, such as the question of how we know we are dreamin=
g and how we know we are awake. It is written in the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Zhuangzi_(book)" title=3D"Zhuangzi (book)">Chuang-tzu</a=
>: "Once Chuang Chou dreamed that he was a butterfly. He fluttered about ha=
ppily, quite pleased with the state that he was in, and knew nothing about =
Chuang Chou. Presently he awoke and found that he was very much Chuang Chou=
 again. Now, did Chou dream that he was a butterfly or was the butterfly no=
w dreaming that he was Chou?"
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Modern_Europe">Modern Europ=
e</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDream_inte=
rpretation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Modern=
 Europe"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<p>In the 17th century, the English physician and writer Sir <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Browne" title=3D"Thomas Browne">Thomas Br=
owne</a> wrote a short tract upon the interpretation of dreams. Dream inter=
pretation became an important part of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Psychoanalysis" title=3D"Psychoanalysis">psychoanalysis</a> at the end =
of the 19th century with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sigmund_F=
reud" title=3D"Sigmund Freud">Sigmund Freud</a>'s seminal work <i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Interpretation_of_Dreams" title=3D"Th=
e Interpretation of Dreams">The Interpretation of Dreams</a></i> (<i>Die Tr=
aumdeutung</i>; literally "dream-interpretation").<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Freud=
,_S._1900_14-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-Freud,_S._1900-14"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
