late">e</abbr></a></li></ul></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>In <i>The Interpretation of Dreams</i>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Sigmund_Freud" title=3D"Sigmund Freud">Sigmund Freud</a> argued th=
at all dream content is disguised <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Wish_fulfillment" title=3D"Wish fulfillment">wish-fulfillment</a> (later in=
 <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beyond_the_Pleasure_Principle"=
 title=3D"Beyond the Pleasure Principle">Beyond the Pleasure Principle</a><=
/i>, Freud would discuss dreams which do not appear to be wish-fulfillment)=
. According to Freud, the instigation of a dream is often to be found in th=
e events of the day preceding the dream, which he called the "day residue."=
 In very young children, this can be easily seen, as they dream quite strai=
ghtforwardly of the fulfillment of wishes that were aroused in them the pre=
vious day (the "dream day"). Sigmund Freud believed that dreams are a way f=
or repressed wishes in the unconscious mind to be expressed. He explained t=
hat the manifest content of a dream is what we remember, while the latent c=
ontent is the hidden meaning behind it. Freud also described a process call=
ed dream-work, which uses methods like condensation, displacement, and symb=
olization to hide unacceptable desires while still allowing them to appear =
in dreams.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In adults the situation is more complicated since, in Freud's analys=
is, the dreams of adults have been subjected to distortion, with the dream'=
s so-called "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Content_(Freudian_dre=
am_analysis)#Manifest_content" title=3D"Content (Freudian dream analysis)">=
manifest content</a>"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-26"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> being a heavily disguised derivative of the "<a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Content_(Freudian_dream_analysis)#Latent_content" title=3D"Co=
ntent (Freudian dream analysis)">latent dream-thoughts</a>"<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_=
interpretation#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> present in the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unconscious_mind" title=3D"Unconscious mind">unconsci=
ous</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The dream'=
s real significance is thus concealed: dreamers are no more capable of reco=
gnizing the actual meaning of their dreams than hysterics are able to under=
stand the connection and significance of their neurotic symptoms.
</p><p>In Freud's original formulation, the latent dream-thought was descri=
bed as having been subject to an intra-psychic force referred to as "the ce=
nsor"; in the terminology of his later years, however, discussion was in te=
rms of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super-ego" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Super-ego">super-ego</a> and the work of the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Id,_ego_and_super-ego" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Id, ego and super-ego">ego</a>'s defence mechanisms. In waking lif=
e, he asserted, these "resistances" prevented the repressed wishes of the u=
nconscious from entering consciousness, and though these wishes were to som=
e extent able to emerge due to the lowered vigilance of the sleep state, th=
e resistances were still strong enough to force them to take on a disguised=
 or distorted form. Freud's view was that dreams are <i>compromises</i> whi=
ch ensure that sleep is not interrupted: as "a <i>disguised</i> fulfilment =
of <i>repressed</i> wishes," they succeed in representing wishes as fulfill=
ed which might otherwise disturb and waken the sleeper.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_inte=
rpretation#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>One of Freud's early dream analyses is "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Irma%27s_injection" title=3D"Irma's injection">Irma's injectio=
n</a>", a dream he himself had. In the dream a former patient of his, Irma,=
 complains of pains and Freud's colleague gives her an unsterile injection.=
  Freud provides pages of associations to the elements in his dream, using =
it to demonstrate his technique of decoding the latent dream thoughts from =
the manifest content of the dream.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-=
30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p><p>Freud suggests that the true meaning of a dream must be "weeded out"=
 from the dream as recalled:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-31"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>You entirely disregard the apparent =
connections between the elements in the manifest dream and collect the idea=
s that occur to you in connection with each separate element of the dream b=
y <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free_association_(psychology)" t=
itle=3D"Free association (psychology)">free association</a> according to th=
e psychoanalytic rule of procedure. From this material you arrive at the la=
tent dream-thoughts, just as you arrived at the patient's hidden complexes =
from his associations to his symptoms and memories... The true meaning of t=
he dream, which has now replaced the manifest content, is always clearly in=
telligible. [Freud, <i>Five Lectures on Psycho-Analysis</i> (1909); Lecture=
 Three]</p></blockquote>
<p>Freud listed the distorting operations that he claimed were applied to r=
epressed wishes in forming the dream as recollected: it is because of these=
 distortions (the so-called "dream-work") that the manifest content of the =
dream differs so greatly from the latent dream thought reached through anal=
ysis=E2=80=94and it is by <i>reversing</i> these distortions that the laten=
t content is approached.
</p><p>The operations included:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-32"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Condensation_(psychology)"=
 title=3D"Condensation (psychology)">Condensation</a> =E2=80=93 one dream o=
bject stands for several associations and ideas; thus "dreams are brief, me=
agre and laconic in comparison with the range and wealth of the dream-thoug=
hts."</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Displacement_(psychology)" tit=
le=3D"Displacement (psychology)">Displacement</a> =E2=80=93 a dream object'=
s emotional significance is separated from its real object or content and a=
ttached to an entirely different one that does not raise the censor's suspi=
cions.</li>
<li>Visualization =E2=80=93 a thought is translated to visual images.</li>
<li>Symbolism =E2=80=93 a symbol replaces an action, person, or idea.</li><=
/ul>
<p>To these might be added "secondary elaboration"=E2=80=94the outcome of t=
he dreamer's natural tendency to make some sort of "sense" or "story" out o=
f the various elements of the manifest content as recollected. Freud stress=
ed that it was not merely futile but actually misleading to attempt to expl=
ain one part of the manifest content with reference to another part, as if =
the manifest dream somehow constituted some unified or coherent conception.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Freud considered that the experience of anxiety dreams and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nightmares" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Nightmares">nightmares</a> was the result of failures in the dream-work=
: rather than contradicting the "wish-fulfillment" theory, such phenomena d=
emonstrated how the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Id,_ego_and_su=
per-ego" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Id, ego and super-ego">ego</a> reac=
ted to the awareness of repressed wishes that were too powerful and insuffi=
ciently disguised. Traumatic dreams (where the dream merely repeats the tra=
umatic experience) were eventually admitted as exceptions to the theory.
</p><p>Freud famously described psychoanalytic dream-interpretation as "the=
 royal road to a knowledge of the unconscious activities of the mind". Howe=
ver, he expressed regret and dissatisfaction at the way his ideas on the su=
bject were misrepresented or simply not understood:
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1244412712"><blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>The assertion that all d=
reams require a sexual interpretation, against which critics rage so incess=
antly, occurs nowhere in my <i>Interpretation of Dreams</i> ... and is in o=
bvious contradiction to other views expressed in it.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpr=
etation#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></p></blockquote>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Jung">Jung</h3><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDream_interpretation&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Jung"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Although not dismissing Freud's model of dream interpretation wholesale,=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Jung" title=3D"Carl Jung">Ca=
rl Jung</a> believed Freud's notion of dreams as representations of unfulfi=
lled wishes to be limited. Jung argued that Freud's procedure of collecting=
 associations to a dream would bring insights into the dreamer's mental com=
plex=E2=80=94a person's associations to anything will reveal the mental com=
plexes, as Jung had shown experimentally<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite=
_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>=E2=80=94but not necessarily closer to the meaning of =
the dream.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Jung was=
 convinced that the scope of dream interpretation was larger, reflecting th=
e richness and complexity of the entire <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Unconscious_mind" title=3D"Unconscious mind">unconscious</a>, both pe=
rsonal and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collective_unconscious"=
 title=3D"Collective unconscious">collective</a>. Jung believed the psyche =
to be a self-regulating organism in which conscious attitudes were likely t=
o be compensated for unconsciously (within the dream) by their opposites.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-Anthony_Storr_1983_37-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-Anthony_Storr_1=
983-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> And so the role of dreams is to lead a person to wholen=
ess through what Jung calls "a dialogue between ego and the self". The self=
 aspires to tell the ego what it does not know, but it should. This dialogu=
e involves fresh memories, existing obstacles, and future solutions.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Jung proposed two basic approaches to analyzing dream material: the =
objective and the subjective.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-39"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> In the objective approach, every person in the dream refers to t=
he person they are: mother is mother, girlfriend is girlfriend, etc.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-:1_40-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-:1-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the subjective=
 approach, every person in the dream represents an aspect of the dreamer. J=
ung argued that the subjective approach is much more difficult for the drea=
mer to accept, but that in most good dream-work, the dreamer will come to r=
ecognize that the dream characters can represent an unacknowledged aspect o=
f the dreamer. Thus, if the dreamer is being chased by a crazed killer, the=
 dreamer may come eventually to recognize his own <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Homicide" title=3D"Homicide">homicidal</a> impulses.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-:1_40-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-:1-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gestalt_therapy" title=3D"Gestalt therapy">Gestalt<=
/a> therapists extended the subjective approach, claiming that even the ina=
nimate objects in a dream can represent aspects of the dreamer.
</p><p>Jung believed that <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archetyp=
es" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Archetypes">archetypes</a> such as the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anima_(Jung)" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Anima (Jung)">animus</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Anima_(Jung)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Anima (Jung)">anima</a>,=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shadow_(psychology)" title=3D=
"Shadow (psychology)">shadow</a>, and others manifested themselves in dream=
s, as dream symbols or figures. Such figures could take the form of an old =
man, a young maiden, or a giant spider as the case may be. Each represents =
an unconscious attitude that is largely hidden to the conscious mind. Altho=
ugh an integral part of the dreamer's psyche, these manifestations were lar=
gely autonomous and were perceived by the dreamer to be external personages=
. Acquaintance with the archetypes as manifested by these symbols serve to =
increase one's awareness of unconscious attitudes, integrating seemingly di=
sparate parts of the psyche and contributing to the process of holistic sel=
f-understanding he considered paramount.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Anthony_Storr_1=
983_37-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drea=
m_interpretation#cite_note-Anthony_Storr_1983-37"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Jung believed that material repressed by the conscious mind, postula=
ted by Freud to comprise the unconscious, was similar to his own concept of=
 the shadow, which in itself is only a small part of the unconscious.
</p><p>Jung cautioned against blindly ascribing meaning to dream symbols wi=
thout a clear understanding of the client's personal situation. He describe=
d two approaches to dream symbols: the causal approach and the final approa=
ch.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the causal a=
pproach, the symbol is reduced to certain fundamental tendencies. Thus, a s=
word may symbolize a penis, as may a snake. In the final approach, the drea=
m interpreter asks, "Why this symbol and not another?" Thus, a sword repres=
enting a penis is hard, sharp, inanimate, and destructive. A snake represen=
ting a penis is alive, dangerous, perhaps poisonous, and slimy. The final a=
pproach will tell additional things about the dreamer's attitudes.
</p><p>Technically, Jung recommended stripping the dream of its details and=
 presenting the gist of the dream to the dreamer. This was an adaptation of=
 a procedure described by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilhelm_=
Stekel" title=3D"Wilhelm Stekel">Wilhelm Stekel</a>, who recommended thinki=
ng of the dream as a newspaper article and writing a headline for it.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Stack_Sullivan" title=3D"Harry Stack Sullivan">Harry=
 Stack Sullivan</a> also described a similar process of "dream distillation=
."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-43" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Although Jung acknowledged the universality of archetypal symbols, h=
e contrasted this with the concept of a sign=E2=80=94images having a one-to=
-one connotation with their meaning. His approach was to recognize the dyna=
mism and fluidity that existed between symbols and their ascribed meaning. =
Symbols must be explored for their personal significance to the patient, in=
stead of having the dream conform to some predetermined idea. This prevents=
 dream analysis from devolving into a theoretical and dogmatic exercise tha=
t is far removed from the patient's own psychological state. In the service=
 of this idea, he stressed the importance of "sticking to the image"=E2=80=
=94exploring in depth a client's association with a particular image. This =
may be contrasted with Freud's free associating which he believed was a dev=
iation from the salience of the image. He describes for example the image "=
deal table." One would expect the dreamer to have some associations with th=
is image, and the professed lack of any perceived significance or familiari=
ty whatsoever should make one suspicious. Jung would ask a patient to imagi=
ne the image as vividly as possible and to explain it to him as if he had n=
o idea as to what a "deal table" was. Jung stressed the importance of conte=
xt in dream analysis.
</p><p>Jung stressed that the dream was not merely a devious puzzle invente=
d by the unconscious to be deciphered, so that the <i>true</i> causal facto=
rs behind it may be elicited. Dreams were not to serve as lie detectors, wi=
th which to reveal the insincerity behind conscious thought processes. Drea=
ms, like the unconscious, had their own language. As representations of the=
 unconscious, dream images have their own primacy and mechanics.
</p><p>Jung believed that dreams may contain ineluctable truths, philosophi=
cal pronouncements, illusions, wild fantasies, memories, plans, irrational =
experiences, and even <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Telepathy" t=
itle=3D"Telepathy">telepathic</a> visions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-44" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#ci=
te_note-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> Just as the psyche has a diurnal side which we expe=
rience as conscious life, it has an unconscious nocturnal side which we app=
rehend as dreamlike fantasy. Jung would argue that just as we do not doubt =
the importance of our conscious experience, then we ought not to second gue=
ss the value of our unconscious lives.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Hall">Hall</h3><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDream_interpretation&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Hall"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In 1953, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calvin_S._Hall" title=
=3D"Calvin S. Hall">Calvin S. Hall</a> developed a theory of dreams in whic=
h dreaming is considered to be a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
ognitive" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cognitive">cognitive</a> process.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-45" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Hall argued that a =
dream was simply a thought or sequence of thoughts that occurred during sle=
ep, and that dream images are visual representations of personal conception=
s. For example, if one dreams of being attacked by friends, this may be a m=
anifestation of fear of friendship; a more complicated example, which requi=
res a cultural metaphor, is that a cat within a dream symbolizes a need to =
use one's intuition. For <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/English_l=
anguage" title=3D"English language">English</a> speakers, it may suggest th=
at the dreamer must recognize that there is "more than one way to skin a ca=
t," or in other words, more than one way to do something. He was also criti=
cal of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sigmund_Freud" title=3D"Sig=
mund Freud">Sigmund Freud's</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ps=
ychoanalytic_theory" title=3D"Psychoanalytic theory">psychoanalytic theory<=
/a> of dream interpretation, particularly Freud's notion that the dream of =
being attacked represented a fear of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Castration" title=3D"Castration">castration</a>. Hall argued that this d=
ream did not necessarily stem from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Castration_anxiety" title=3D"Castration anxiety">castration anxiety</a>, b=
ut rather represented the dreamer's perception of themselves as weak, passi=
ve, and helpless in the face of danger.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-46" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_=
note-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> In support of his argument, Hall pointed out that wome=
n have this dream more frequently than men, yet women do not typically expe=
rience <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Castration_anxiety" title=
=3D"Castration anxiety">castration anxiety</a>. Additionally, he noted that=
 there were no significant differences in the form or content of the dream =
of being attacked between men and women, suggesting that the dream likely h=
as the same meaning for both genders. Hall's work in dream research also pr=
ovided evidence to support one of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Sigmund_Freud" title=3D"Sigmund Freud">Sigmund Freud's</a> theories, the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oedipus_complex" title=3D"Oedipus co=
mplex">Oedipus Complex</a>. Hall studied the dreams of males and females ag=
es two through twenty-six. He found that young boys frequently dreamed of a=
ggression towards their fathers and older male siblings, while girls dreame=
d of hostility towards their mothers and older female siblings.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dr=
eam_interpretation#cite_note-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> These dreams often involved th=
emes of conflict and competition for the affection of the opposite-sex pare=
nt, providing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Empirical_evidence" =
title=3D"Empirical evidence">empirical support</a> for Freud's theory of th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oedipus_complex" title=3D"Oedipu=
s complex">Oedipus Complex</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Faraday,_Clift,_et_al."><sp=
an id=3D"Faraday.2C_Clift.2C_et_al."></span>Faraday, Clift, et al.</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDream_interpretation=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Faraday, Clift,=
 et al."><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<p>In the 1970s, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ann_Faraday" titl=
e=3D"Ann Faraday">Ann Faraday</a> and others helped bring dream interpretat=
ion into the mainstream by publishing books on do-it-yourself dream interpr=
etation and forming groups to share and analyze dreams. Faraday focused on =
the application of dreams to situations occurring in one's life. For instan=
ce, some dreams are warnings of something about to happen=E2=80=94e.g. a dr=
eam of failing an examination, if one is a student, may be a literal warnin=
g of unpreparedness. Outside of such context, it could relate to failing so=
me other kind of test. Or it could even have a "<a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Pun" title=3D"Pun">punny</a>" nature, e.g. that one has faile=
d to examine some aspect of his life adequately.
</p><p>Faraday noted that "one finding has emerged pretty firmly from moder=
n research, namely that the majority of dreams seem in some way to reflect =
things that have preoccupied our minds during the previous day or two."<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the 1980s and 1990s, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wal=
lace_Clift" title=3D"Wallace Clift">Wallace Clift</a> and <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean_Dalby_Clift" title=3D"Jean Dalby Clift">Jean D=
alby Clift</a> further explored the relationship between images produced in=
 dreams and the dreamer's waking life. Their books identified patterns in d=
reaming, and ways of analyzing dreams to explore life changes, with particu=
lar emphasis on moving toward healing and wholeness.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-49"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpr=
etation#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Neurobiological_theory">Neu=
robiological theory</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DDream_interpretation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"E=
dit section: Neurobiological theory"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allan_Hobson" title=3D"Allan Ho=
bson">Allan Hobson</a> and colleagues developed what they called the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Activation-synthesis_hypothesis" title=
=3D"Activation-synthesis hypothesis">activation-synthesis hypothesis</a> wh=
ich proposes that dreams are simply the side effects of the neural activity=
 in the brain that produces <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beta_b=
rain_wave" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Beta brain wave">beta brain waves=
</a> during <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/REM_sleep" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"REM sleep">REM sleep</a> that are associated with wakef=
ulness. According to this hypothesis, neurons fire periodically during slee=
p in the lower brain levels and thus send random signals to the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cortex_(anatomy)" title=3D"Cortex (anatomy)">=
cortex</a>. The cortex then synthesizes a dream in reaction to these signal=
s in order to try to make sense of why the brain is sending them. Although =
the hypothesis downplays the role that emotional factors play in determinin=
g dreams, it does not state that dreams are meaningless.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-Weiten166_50-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-Weiten166-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Present-day_popular_attitud=
es">Present-day popular attitudes</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DDream_interpretation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D=
13" title=3D"Edit section: Present-day popular attitudes"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Most people currently appear to interpret dream content according to <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Interpretation_of_Dreams" title=
=3D"The Interpretation of Dreams">Freudian psychoanalysis</a> in the United=
 States, India, and South Korea, according to one study conducted in those =
countries.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_51-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-:0-51"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 People appear to believe dreams are particularly meaningful: they assign m=
ore meaning to dreams than to similar waking thoughts. For example, people =
report they would be more likely to cancel a trip they had planned that inv=
olved a plane flight if they dreamt of their plane crashing the night befor=
e than if the Department of Homeland Security issued a federal warning.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-:0_51-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-:0-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, peopl=
e do not attribute equal importance to all dreams. People appear to use <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motivated_reasoning" title=3D"Motivat=
ed reasoning">motivated reasoning</a> when interpreting their dreams. They =
are more likely to view dreams confirming their waking beliefs and desires =
to be more meaningful than dreams that contradict their waking beliefs and =
desires.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_51-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-:0-51"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A paper<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_51-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_interpretation#cite_note-:0-51"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> in 2009 by Carey Morewedge and Michael Norton in the <i>Journal of Pers=
onality and Social Psychology</i> found that most people believe that "thei=
r dreams reveal meaningful hidden truths." In one study they found that 74%=
 of Indians, 65% of South Koreans and 56% of Americans believed their dream=
 content provided them with meaningful insight into their unconscious belie=
fs and desires. This Freudian view of dreaming was endorsed significantly m=
ore than theories of dreaming that attribute dream content to memory consol=
idation, problem solving, or random brain activity. This belief appears to =
lead people to attribute more importance to dream content than to similar t=
hought content that occurs while they are awake. People were more likely to=
 view a positive dream about a friend to be meaningful than a positive drea=
m about someone they disliked, for example, and were more likely to view a =
negative dream about a person they disliked as meaningful than a negative d=
ream about a person they liked.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Layne_Dalfen" title=3D"Layn=
e Dalfen">Layne Dalfen</a>, a contemporary dream analyst and educator, has =
significantly contributed to the modern understanding of dream interpretati=
on. She developed the <i>Six Points of Entry</i> method, which provides pra=
ctical tools for analyzing dreams. This method helps individuals uncover th=
e emotional significance and potential solutions that dreams may offer, emp=
hasizing their role in personal growth and problem-solving. Through her Dre=
am Interpretation Center, media appearances, online course and books, Dalfe=
n has made dream analysis accessible to a broader audience.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-52" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_=
interpretation#cite_note-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
